,[\"$\",\"meta\",\"12\",{\"property\":\"og:image:height\",\"content\":\"630\"}],[\"$\",\"meta\",\"13\",{\"name\":\"twitter:card\",\"content\":\"summary_large_image\"}],[\"$\",\"meta\",\"14\",{\"name\":\"twitter:title\",\"content\":\"it's my following and i want it my way! ‚Äî mmatt.net\"}],[\"$\",\"meta\",\"15\",{\"name\":\"twitter:description\",\"content\":\"by Matt ¬∑ 6 min read\"}],[\"$\",\"meta\",\"16\",{\"name\":\"twitter:image:type\",\"content\":\"image/png\"}],[\"$\",\"meta\",\"17\",{\"name\":\"twitter:image\",\"content\":\"https://mmatt.net/post/3mcvlmb65dc2s/opengraph-image?94a7d1ebf9fe9d11\"}],[\"$\",\"meta\",\"18\",{\"name\":\"twitter:image:width\",\"content\":\"1200\"}],[\"$\",\"meta\",\"19\",{\"name\":\"twitter:image:height\",\"content\":\"630\"}],[\"$\",\"link\",\"20\",{\"rel\":\"icon\",\"href\":\"/favicon.ico\",\"type\":\"image/x-icon\",\"sizes\":\"16x16\"}],[\"$\",\"$L3a\",\"21\",{}]],\"error\":null,\"digest\":\"$undefined\"}\ne:\"$9:metadata\"\n13:[\"$\",\"p\",\"0\",{\"className\":\"font-sans text-pretty leading-7 not-first:mt-6\",\"children\":[\"So last week \",[\"$\",\"span\",\"segment-0\",{\"children\":[\"$\",\"a\",\"link-0\",{\"href\":\"https://sprk.so\",\"className\":\"font-medium underline underline-offset-4\",\"children\":\"Spark Social\"}]}],\" announced their Open Beta and with that their separated social graph.\"]}]\n15:[\"$\",\"p\",\"2\",{\"className\":\"font-sans text-pretty leading-7 not-first:mt-6\",\"children\":[\"This choice ended up starting a bunch of discussion about how we should be using the social graph in the ATmosphere. More specifically I remember these posts from \",[\"$\",\"span\",\"segment-0\",{\"children\":\"@dame.is\"}],\" and \",[\"$\",\"span\",\"segment-1\",{\"children\":\"@iame.li\"}],\". Between the two posts, I definitely lean towards dame's post. And I hope this post explains my vision behind that reasoning.\"]}]\n18:[\"$\",\"p\",\"5\",{\"className\":\"font-sans text-pretty leading-7 not-first:mt-6\",\"children\":[\"This whole debacle \",[\"$\",\"span\",\"segment-0\",{\"children\":[\"$\",\"em\",\"italic-0\",{\"children\":\"sparked\"}]}],\" a lot of thoughts in my mind about how we do social graphs in the social internet, and how a shared account (your ATProto repository) that you use to login to multiple services (Bluesky, Tangled, Streamplace, Leaflet, etc.) should handle your social graph. One of the benefits we bring up for ATProto's superiority is that \",[\"$\",\"span\",\"segment-1\",{\"children\":[\"$\",\"em\",\"italic-1\",{\"children\":\"you\"}]}],\" own your social graph, but what happens when the apps decide \",[\"$\",\"span\",\"segment-2\",{\"children\":[\"$\",\"em\",\"italic-2\",{\"children\":\"how\"}]}],\" your social graph is used? I know this is kinda \",[\"$\",\"span\",\"segment-3\",{\"children\":[\"$\",\"a\",\"link-3\",{\"href\":\"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/necropost\",\"className\":\"font-medium underline underline-offset-4\",\"children\":\"necroposting\"}]}],\" but I wanted this out of my mind and onto paper. \"]}]\n19:[\"$\",\"h1\",\"6\",{\"className\":\"font-serif font-bold text-balance tracking-tight scroll-m-20 mt-8 [&>code]:text-[length:inherit] first:mt-0 text-4xl lg:text-5xl\",\"children\":\"Old Social: Different venues, different music.\"}]\n1a:[\"$\",\"span\",\"7\",{\"className\":\"block mt-8 w-full aspect-video relative\",\"children\":[\"$\",\"$L11\",null,{\"src\":\"https://cdn.bsky.app/img/feed_fullsize/plain/did:plc:tas6hj2xjrqben5653v5kohk/bafkreiau2u7aamrdduuwvvwrljjei4wmbflv23mwdqjqdkhtzyliegg5ym@jpeg\",\"alt\":\"\",\"className\":\"object-contain\",\"quality\":90,\"fill\":true}]}]\n1b:[\"$\",\"p\",\"8\",{\"className\":\"font-sans text-pretty leading-7 not-first:mt-6\",\"children\":\"In old social land, my social graph is separated per account each with a different login. Instagram doesn't know about my YouTube followers, TikTok doesn't know who I'm following on Instagram, etc.\"}]\n1c:[\"$\",\"p\",\"9\",{\"className\":\"font-sans text-pretty leading-7 not-first:mt-6\",\"children\":\"Anecdotally speaking, each of these apps have very different usage for most people. Most people use Instagram for connecting with personal friends and family and sharing moments of their life, they use YouTube for entertainment, and TikTok for short form quick entertainment.\"}]\n1d:[\"$\",\"p\",\"10\",{\"className\":\"font-sans text-pretty leading-7 not-first:mt-6\",\"children\":\"If each of these apps knew about the other's social graph, my Instagram feed gets cluttered with public figures and entertainment, and my TikTok feed gets cluttered with people I know.\"}]\n1e:[\"$\",\"p\",\"11\",{\"className\":\"font-sans text-pretty leading-7 not-first:mt-6\",\"children\":[\"To some people that doesn't matter to them, but to me each app is specifically tailored to the content I want to see. If my Instagram social graph is \",[\"$\",\"span\",\"segment-0\",{\"children\":[\"$\",\"em\",\"italic-0\",{\"children\":\"also\"}]}],\" my YouTube social graph, the little control I have over the content I see starts slipping more and more. Like sure I love LTT videos but I don't need to see their Instagram content too.\"]}]\n1f:[\"$\",\"h1\",\"12\",{\"className\":\"font-serif font-bold text-balance tracking-tight scroll-m-20 mt-8 [&>code]:text-[length:inherit] first:mt-0 text-4xl lg:text-5xl\",\"children\":\"New Social: We're all breathing the same air in the ATmosphere.\"}]\n20:[\"$\",\"p\",\"13\",{\"className\":\"font-sans text-pretty leading-7 not-first:mt-6\",\"children\":\"In old social land, none of these accounts are connected in any way. @mmatt on Twitter isn't connected to @mmattbtw on Twitch which isn't connected to @mmattbtw on YouTube.\"}]\n21:[\"$\",\"p\",\"14\",{\"className\":\"font-sans text-pretty leading-7 not-first:mt-6\",\"children\":\"In the new social world, your identity holds everything. My Bluesky content is posted by the same identity that posts my Leaflet blogs that is posted by the same identity which chats in Streamplace streams. \"}]\n22:[\"$\",\"span\",\"15\",{\"className\":\"block mt-8 w-full aspect-video relative\",\"children\":[\"$\",\"$L11\",null,{\"src\":\"https://cdn.bsky.app/img/feed_fullsize/plain/did:plc:tas6hj2xjrqben5653v5kohk/bafkreiggsv26wum7spr6ixxvzy23z6vvkpgy3op7z7hfogyx33373yq3n4@jpeg\",\"alt\":\"\",\"className\":\"object-contain\",\"quality\":90,\"fill\":true}]}]\n23:[\"$\",\"p\",\"16\",{\"className\":\"font-sans text-pretty leading-7 not-first:mt-6\",\"children\":[\"When you \\\"Follow\\\" someone on Twitter, you're following the \",[\"$\",\"span\",\"segment-0\",{\"children\":[\"$\",\"em\",\"italic-0\",{\"children\":\"Twitter\"}]}],\" \",[\"$\",\"span\",\"segment-1\",{\"children\":[\"$\",\"em\",\"italic-1\",{\"children\":\"account\"}]}],\", not the person. In the new social world, when you follow someone on Bluesky, technically, you are following the \",[\"$\",\"span\",\"segment-2\",{\"children\":[\"$\",\"em\",\"italic-2\",{\"children\":\"person\"}]}],\" with the \",[\"$\",\"span\",\"segment-3\",{\"children\":[\"$\",\"em\",\"italic-3\",{\"children\":\"intent\"}]}],\" of keeping up with them specifically on Bluesky.\"]}]\n24:[\"$\",\"p\",\"17\",{\"className\":\"font-sans text-pretty leading-7 not-first:mt-6\",\"children\":\"For all intensive purposes, these two mean the same thing to the user. But when thinking about it from outside of the apps itself, the relationship made is more interesting.\"}]\n25:[\"$\",\"span\",\"18\",{\"className\":\"block mt-8 w-full aspect-video relative\",\"children\":[\"$\",\"$L11\",null,{\"src\":\"https://cdn.bsky.app/img/feed_fullsize/plain/did:plc:tas6hj2xjrqben5653v5kohk/bafkreihtddebivw3hlare5bzm5rapyrihdsx4rzuq3a6b66c4k5x2mrg24@jpeg\",\"alt\":\"\",\"className\":\"object-contain\",\"quality\":90,\"fill\":true}]}]\n26:[\"$\",\"p\",\"19\",{\"className\":\"font-sans text-pretty leading-7 not-first:mt-6\",\"children\":[\"This person your account is following on Bluesky might also use other apps on that identity, but your \\\"follow\\\" is only intended for Bluesky via the \",[\"$\",\"span\",\"segment-0\",{\"children\":[\"$\",\"code\",\"code-0\",{\"className\":\"font-mono normal-case relative rounded-sm px-[0.3rem] py-[0.2rem] bg-slate-100 text-sm dark:bg-slate-800 dark:text-slate-100\",\"children\":\"app.bsky.graph.follow\"}]}],\" lexicon. Your relationship is also visible to these other apps, whether these apps \",[\"$\",\"span\",\"segment-1\",{\"children\":[\"$\",\"em\",\"italic-1\",{\"children\":\"choose\"}]}],\" to look at this relationship is up to the developer.\"]}]\n27:[\"$\",\"p\",\"20\",{\"className\":\"font-sans text-pretty leading-7 not-first:mt-6\",\"children\":[\"So where should the control go? In my eyes, lexicons are intent based, and should be scoped towards the applications they are intended for. This is why \",[\"$\",\"span\",\"segment-0\",{\"children\":[\"$\",\"a\",\"link-0\",{\"href\":\"https://lexicon.community\",\"className\":\"font-medium underline underline-offset-4\",\"children\":\"lexicon.community\"}]}],\" never really stuck to me, applications and lexicons to me should be heavily opinionated with how they want their applications shaped.\"]}]\n28:[\"$\",\"h1\",\"21\",{\"className\":\"font-serif font-bold text-balance tracking-tight scroll-m-20 mt-8 [&>code]:text-[length:inherit] first:mt-0 text-4xl lg:text-5xl\",\"children\":\"ON THE OTHER HAND: BLOGS, WRITING, AND OTHER LONG WRITING MEDIUMS.\"}]\n29:[\"$\",\"p\",\"22\",{\"className\":\"font-sans text-pretty leading-7 not-first:mt-6\",\"children\":[\"Something in my brain clicked when \",[\"$\",\"span\",\"segment-0\",{\"children\":[\"$\",\"a\",\"link-0\",{\"href\":\"https://standard.site\",\"className\":\"font-medium underline underline-offset-4\",\"children\":\"standard.site\"}]}],\" launched however. And I think thats because the writing medium is so standardized. Text on screen with formatting and authors, everything else is on the side. Why shouldn't my WhiteWind posts and Leaflet posts be able to be read in the same place? \"]}]\n2a:[\"$\",\"p\",\"23\",{\"className\":\"font-sans text-pretty leading-7 not-first:mt-6\",\"children\":[\"Matter of fact, they can! On \",[\"$\",\"span\",\"segment-0\",{\"children\":[\"$\",\"a\",\"link-0\",{\"href\":\"https://mmatt.net/writing\",\"className\":\"font-medium underline underline-offset-4\",\"children\":\"mmatt.net/writing\"}]}],\", this post (on Leaflet), my WhiteWind posts, my Teal Notes post are all viewable in one location. Each of these pieces come from different contexts, so for outside posts not meant for the exact context of publishing onto my site have a little disclaimer saying \\\"this was written over here, view the original.\\\" Of course you can still view the post in its entirety on mmatt.net, everything still works just like it would over here on Leaflet.pub.\"]}]\n2b:[\"$\",\"p\",\"24\",{\"className\":\"font-sans text-pretty leading-7 not-first:mt-6\",\"children\":\"So, when it comes to writing, I actually flip on the whole social graph take. Being able to \\\"follow\\\" an individual author that might post on one publication via Leaflet, or make a guest post on another publication via Offprint, I should be able to follow my author across the ATmosphere and be able to see all their writing in one place.\"}]\n2c:[\"$\",\"p\",\"25\",{\"className\":\"font-sans text-pretty leading-7 not-first:mt-6\",\"children\":[\"What if, \",[\"$\",\"span\",\"segment-0\",{\"children\":[\"$\",\"code\",\"code-0\",{\"className\":\"font-mono normal-case relative rounded-sm px-[0.3rem] py-[0.2rem] bg-slate-100 text-sm dark:bg-slate-800 dark:text-slate-100\",\"children\":\"site.standard.graph.author.follow\"}]}],\", let me follow an individual author across all of their \",[\"$\",\"span\",\"segment-1\",{\"children\":[\"$\",\"a\",\"link-1\",{\"href\":\"https://standard.site\",\"className\":\"font-medium underline underline-offset-4\",\"children\":\"standard.site\"}]}],\" publications. Writing usually doesn't have the explicit context shifts of long form / short form video, or microblogging, or live streaming, etc. A lot of people consume blogs, news, and other forms of long writing through RSS readers which ultimately eliminates the context of whatever site or platform the piece was written for. And I think this works perfectly for writing.\"]}]\n2d:[\"$\",\"p\",\"26\",{\"className\":\"font-sans text-pretty leading-7 not-first:mt-6\",\"children\":[\"In the same sense, what if \",[\"$\",\"span\",\"segment-0\",{\"children\":[\"$\",\"code\",\"code-0\",{\"className\":\"font-mono normal-case relative rounded-sm px-[0.3rem] py-[0.2rem] bg-slate-100 text-sm dark:bg-slate-800 dark:text-slate-100\",\"children\":\"site.standard.graph.publication.follow\"}]}],\". Similar to an RSS feed just let me keep up with an entire publication on any reading platform. \",[\"$\",\"span\",\"segment-1\",{\"children\":[\"$\",\"a\",\"link-1\",{\"href\":\"https://bsky.app/profile/brookie.blog/post/3mccxb7fjo22d\",\"className\":\"font-medium underline underline-offset-4\",\"children\":\"(I think this is already a thing?)\"}]}]]}]\n2e:[\"$\",\"p\",\"27\",{\"className\":\"font-sans text-pretty leading-7 not-first:mt-6\",\"children\":\"For some reason, only in this context do shared social graphs make sense to me. When you're all using a standardized lexicon and interop is the default, this just makes sense to do.\"}]\n2f:[\"$\",\"h1\",\"28\",{\"className\":\"font-serif font-bold text-balance tracking-tight scroll-m-20 mt-8 [&>code]:text-[length:inherit] first:mt-0 text-4xl lg:text-5xl\",\"children\":\"The case for \\\"genre based\\\" following instead of global following.\"}]\n30:[\"$\",\"p\",\"29\",{\"className\":\"font-sans text-pretty leading-7 not-first:mt-6\",\"children\":[\"I think the example above with following an author for their writing is a great case for a genre based social graph system \",[\"$\",\"span\",\"segment-0\",{\"children\":[\"$\",\"em\",\"italic-0\",{\"children\":\"instead\"}]}],\" of a global social graph.\"]}]\n32:[\"$\",\"p\",\"31\",{\"className\":\"font-sans text-pretty leading-7 not-first:mt-6\",\"children\":[\"I think this post from \",[\"$\",\"span\",\"segment-0\",{\"children\":\"@iame.li\"}],\" perfectly frames how I view this. If there are multiple streaming services, let me follow once and view that streamer on all the platforms. If there is an artist I find on \",[\"$\",\"span\",\"segment-1\",{\"children\":[\"$\",\"a\",\"link-1\",{\"href\":\"https://plyr.fm\",\"className\":\"font-medium underline underline-offset-4\",\"children\":\"plyr.fm\"}]}],\", why not be able to keep that relationship to another music platform?\"]}]\n33:[\"$\",\"p\",\"32\",{\"className\":\"font-sans text-pretty leading-7 not-first:mt-6\",\"children\":\"Global following on the other hand still doesn't sit right with me. I appreciate getting updates on some brands on Bluesky, but do I need their livestreams or short videos in their respective apps? Not in my mind.\"}]\n34:[\"$\",\"p\",\"33\",{\"className\":\"font-sans text-pretty leading-7 not-first:mt-6\",\"children\":\"I think in either situation (genre or global) user control is still key. The UX of that would take some time to plan out, and out of scope for this post (because I want this out asap lol).\"}]\n35:[\"$\",\"hr\",\"34\",{\"className\":\"my-8\"}]\n36:[\"$\",\"p\",\"35\",{\"className\":\"font-sans text-pretty leading-7 not-first:mt-6\",\"children\":\"AT THE END OF THE DAY, ITS JUST SOCIAL MEDIA RIGHT?\"}]\n37:[\"$\",\"p\",\"36\",{\"className\":\"font-sans text-pretty leading-7 not-first:mt-6\",\"children\":\"I think I derailed at the end here, but feel free to ask questions about anything in the post, would be more than happy to clarify!\"}]\n38:[\"$\",\"p\",\"37\",{\"className\":\"font-sans text-pretty leading-7 not-first:mt-6\",\"children\":\"thanks for reading >_>\"}]\n39:[\"$\",\"p\",\"38\",{\"className\":\"font-sans text-pretty leading-7 not-first:mt-6\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"span\",\"segment-0\",{\"children\":\